data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType<T>()` (MSTest v3+). It combines the type check and cast, and gives a clearer failure message:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();

    var handler = Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(factory.Create("email"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

The generic overload returns the cast object, so you can keep asserting on it. No manual cast or separate null check needed. If the type is wrong, the test fails with a descriptive message instead of throwing an `InvalidCastException`.
